body_raw:
Well, in this question it is said that $\sqrt[100]{\sqrt3 + \sqrt2} + \sqrt[100]{\sqrt3 - \sqrt2}$ , and the owner asks for "alternative proofs" which do not use rational root theorem. I wrote an answer, but I just proved $\sqrt[100]{\sqrt3 + \sqrt2} 
otin \mathbb{Q}$ and $\sqrt[100]{\sqrt3 - \sqrt2} 
otin \mathbb{Q}$ , not the sum of them. I got (fairly) downvoted, because I didn't notice that the sum of two irrational can be either rational or irrational, and I deleted my (incorrect) answer. So, I want help in proving things like $\sqrt5 + \sqrt7 
otin \mathbb{Q}$ , and $(1 + \pi) - \pi \in \mathbb{Q}$ , if there is any "trick" or rule to these cases of summing two (or more) known irrational numbers (without rational root theorem). Thanks.
